This was test fired from Colt, that is it. This is complete with FCG, Factory H buffer, spring and stock. Factory Ambi-Safety, roll marked "M4A1 CARBINE". These were a limited production run and have not been made in about 6 years. These demand a premium based on their collectibility and how rare they are. I will ship at buyers expense to an FFL and only accept paypal friends and family or USPS money orders. This is a serialized part and is considered a firearm by the BATFE. I will meet you in person at an FFL or will sell to NH residents with a valid NHDL and CCWP. Again, CASH ONLY, I DO NOT WANT ANY TRADES!!!

title: For Sale:  ARISAKA TYPE 3O CARBINE
postcontent: Offered for sale is a scarce original Japanese Type 30 Carbine. These carbines (and rifles) were based upon the German Mauser action and were the brainchild of Colonel Nariake Arisaka. The prototypes were submitted in 1896 and full production began "in the 30th year of ruling Meiji-emperor", translating to the year 1897 in western calendar terms. Full approval was given to the Japanese military two years later.These weapons saw use in Russo-Japanese war of 1904/1905 and also [reportedly] WWI and WWII. They appear to have been manufactured between 1897 and about 1902. The total production run of Type 30 infantry rifles seems to have been over 500,000 rifles, while the total production of carbines is estimated only around 40,000.Japan sold these rifles and carbines in large numbers to Great Britain and Russia during WWI. "In Great Britain M/97 rifles were issued [to] training units, Navy and Flying Corps and known as 'Rifle, Magazine, .256 Pattern 1900.' Suffering from even more disastrous shortage of rifles the Russians could not afford to issue these rifles only as training equipment. So they issued Japanese rifles also as part of usual weaponry issued mainly to their non-frontline units, this included their troops stationed in Finland.Finland used about 8,000 infantry rifles and a minuscule amount of carbines M/97 during the Finnish Civil War of 1918. Suojeluskunta (Finnish Civil Guard) used some in 1920's. The most distinct feature is the hook-shaped safety in bolt head (other than that they appear very similar to the Japanese Type 38 series).Based upon the German Mauser action with some Mannlicher influence, bolt-action with hook safety, 19" barrel, made from 1897 to 1902. Caliber is 6.50mm x 50R Arisaka, five-round fixed magazine with spring-loaded floor-plate.NOTE: Cleaning rod is missing on this example.This rifle was manufactured in 1897. This rifle was not decommisioned, appears to have been brought back by a soldier. Looks to have been used as a service weapon. This rifle is untested. Shows lots of signs of wear. Great patina and character. Please see pictures.Shipping to FFL of your choice is available for $40.00 in the lower 48. Insurance is available at purchasers expense. There is a 4% credit card fee.Please contact me with any other questions. More pictures are available upon request. Larry REDACTED.
